Ok, your snapshot is corrupted. Did your node crash or anything similar?

We can probably trigger a snapshot check/fixup, but I need to see which snapshot metadata entries your node has. Could you run these?

```
geth db get 0x536e617073686f7444697361626c6564
geth db get 0x536e617073686f74526f6f74
geth db get 0x536e617073686f744a6f75726e616c
geth db get 0x536e617073686f7447656e657261746f72
geth db get 0x536e617073686f745265636f76657279
geth db get 0x536e617073686f7453796e63537461747573
```

EDIT: Added 2 more

> Not sure if any of this info can harm me or exposes something about my node.

It's only snapshot related metadata

`0x536e617073686f7444697361626c6564` -- `SnapshotDisabled`
`0x536e617073686f74526f6f74`- `SnapshotRoot`
`0x536e617073686f744a6f75726e616c` - `SnapshotJournal`
`0x536e617073686f7447656e657261746f72` - `SnapshotGenerator`
`0x536e617073686f745265636f76657279` - `SnapshotRecovery`
 `536e617073686f7453796e63537461747573` - `SnapshotSyncStatus`

@anondinh Ok, so if you run `geth db delete 0x536e617073686f74526f6f74`, this will delete the database key which contains the state root of the snapshot. When Geth starts up and doesn't find this, it will start regenerating the entire snapshot, but will reuse any existing data. I'm certain that it will still take a good few hours even like this, but at least you'll have a functional node (generation will be done in the background) without needing a resync.

Thank you for providing help, I ran the command and restarted geth.
It seems to be regenerating fine and not loop the invalid block, if nothing fails I will close this issue once it is running properly again
